    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>And if you neither want to use @Autowire nor injecting @Value you can simply do (with fallback included):</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>System.getProperty(&quot;spring.profiles.active&quot;, &quot;unknown&quot;);\n</code></pre>\n<p>This will return any active profile (or fallback to 'unknown').</p>\n<hr />\n<p>This however doesn't work out-of-the-box. The Spring profile must be somehow set to the system property. That's why it works for someone and not for everybody. I did assume that OP uses spring profiles in active fashion, i.e., setting a profile deliberately e.g., &quot;test&quot;, &quot;dev&quot;, &quot;prod&quot; etc. This is done with settings/properties, in Java config files and/or in command line when running boot:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-none prettyprint-override\"><code>java -Dspring.profiles.active=&lt;your-profile&gt; ... &lt;your-main-class&gt;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
